      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4496ec4eaa9cf3e5",
      "text": "Bypassing abstraction leads to the choice of redundancy models that seem so alien to us that they are initially hard to comprehend – just as a state of pure orality is hard to comprehend when one has writing at one's disposal (even when one is not using writing at the moment, as in the case of an oral interaction among attendants). […]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "36ca12b9d32327df",
      "text": "[…] The discrimination of phonetics and non-phonetics may seem strange at first, but it is justified on the one hand by the fact that alphabetic scripts, i.e. scripts whose characters are assigned to certain sounds, are accompanied by fundamental changes in the organization of memory (this will be discussed in detail in the following chapter). For this reason, too, they must be distinguished from non-phonetic scripts. On the other hand, any form of written fixation of communication enables the distinction between the recursivity of observations and the recursivity of operations, and in this way leads to the formation of its own structures. In the absence of an accomplished phonetism, recursivity inevitably remains context-bound and cannot yet include the distinction of the level of words from the level of objects (the self-reference and foreign-reference of communication); it nevertheless leads to an \"accumulation\" of observations and thus to an influence on communication, which in the course of time becomes more and more presuppositional. richer in the course of time. What communication observes, that is, what is talked about, is therefore anything but simple-minded and structured according to forms that are context-dependent but by no means exclusively taken from the context. This is already sufficient to be able to assume an independent memory."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "991de3901d5e052d",
      "text": "The characteristics of non-phonetic writing can help to discern the underlying structures. We think first of the abstract case of \"pictograms\": signs that stand directly for objects – but also of ideograms, signs that stand for semantic units, ideas, or models of other kinds. In both cases, to use Bottéro's terminology, they are *thing-writings* and not *word-writings* – communication is not transmitted, but certain objects are reproduced in permanent forms (on which one can work). The advantage offered by these scripts is that they can be \"read\" independently of the spoken language: the case of China, where since the 3rd century BC there are uniform writing norms that allow the same texts to be read aloud in different dialects. The indifference to phonetic transformations (especially in the case of China, to which we will return) allows the continuity of written traditions and a particular kind of \"accumulation\" of materials."
