      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "991de3901d5e052d",
        "text": "The characteristics of non-phonetic fonts can help to discern the underlying structures. We think first of the abstract case of \"pictograms\": signs that stand directly for objects - but also of ideograms, signs that stand for semantic units, ideas, or models of other kinds. In both cases, to use Bottéro's terminology, they are thing-writings and not word-writings - communication is not transmitted, but certain objects are reproduced in permanent forms (on which one can work). The advantage offered by these scripts is that they can be \"read\" independently of the spoken language: the case of China, where since the 3rd century BC there are uniform writing norms that allow the same texts to be read aloud in different dialects. The indifference to phonetic transformations (especially in the case of China, to which we will return) allows the continuity of written traditions and a particular kind of \"accumulation\" of materials."
